what are the best ai integration options for neovim? I'm very interested in, eg, being able to have a claude or gemini chat *with my web subscription rate, not some per-token billed api bullshit* so that instead of having to navigate the conversation with some shitty proprietary website or tui I can use neovim navigation.

I hear you—there is nothing more annoying than paying $20/month for a "Pro" web subscription only to be hit with a separate per-token bill just because you want to use the model in your editor.

The short answer is: Official web subscriptions and API keys are fundamentally separate. Claude and Gemini do not provide a "legal" way to use your web session inside Neovim. However, there are three distinct ways to bypass the "per-token bullshit" using Neovim.

1. The "Native" Way: GitHub Copilot
If you want a flat-rate subscription that "just works" in Neovim, GitHub Copilot ($10/mo) is the only one with first-class support.

The Hack: Modern plugins like avante.nvim or codecompanion.nvim can use your Copilot subscription as the "provider" to give you a chat interface and inline edits without extra costs.

The Catch: You are stuck with Copilot's models (usually GPT-4o or Claude 3.5 Sonnet), and it’s not using your direct Claude.ai or Gemini Advanced subscription.

2. The "Bridge" Way: Claude Code & Gemini CLI
In early 2026, both Anthropic and Google released official CLI agents (Claude Code and Gemini CLI). These are designed to live in your terminal and are often included in certain subscription tiers or have much higher "free" ceilings than the raw API.

avante.nvim: This is currently the "Cursor for Neovim" heavyweight. It has built-in ACP (Agent Client Protocol) support. It can literally "spawn" the Claude Code or Gemini CLI process in the background and pipe the chat into a Neovim buffer.

Why this fits you: You get the Neovim keybindings and navigation you want, but the heavy lifting is done by the CLI tool rather than a metered API call.

3. The "Free Tier" Strategy: Gemini 2.0 / 1.5 Flash
If your "bullshit" meter is mostly about the cost, Google Gemini is currently the best "loophole."

The Strategy: Use gemini-cli.nvim or codecompanion.nvim with a Gemini API key.

The Cost: Google offers a massive free tier for Gemini 1.5 Flash (and often 2.0 Flash) through Google AI Studio. It allows for thousands of requests per day for free, provided you're okay with them using your data for tuning (similar to the web subscription).

Navigation: You get full Neovim motions, Markdown rendering, and project context without paying a cent beyond your internet bill.

My Recommendation
If you want the absolute best UX with the least amount of "token-counting" anxiety, go with Avante.nvim using the Gemini 1.5 Flash (via AI Studio) or Claude Code integration.

Quick Start with Avante (Lazy.nvim)
Lua
{
  "yetone/avante.nvim",
  event = "VeryLazy",
  opts = {
    provider = "gemini", -- Or "claude" if using Claude Code
    gemini = {
      model = "gemini-1.5-flash", -- Virtually free/high quota
      max_tokens = 4096,
    },
  },
}
One final note: If you're looking for a plugin that literally "scrapes" your browser session to use your $20/month Claude.ai chat, those exist (look for "browser-cookie" based adapters in gp.nvim), but they break constantly because Anthropic/Google hate them. Using the CLI agents is the more stable way to get "subscription-like" behavior in the terminal.

