so avante with gemini would be a bit like cursor?

Yes, Avante.nvim is essentially the "Neovim flavor of Cursor."

It doesn't just give you a chat window; it attempts to replicate the specific "Agentic" workflow that made Cursor famous. Since you're looking to avoid the "per-token bullshit" while keeping the power of the latest models (like Gemini 3), this is exactly the tool you want.

Here is how Avante compares to Cursor and why it solves your problem:

1. The "Cursor" Features in Neovim
The Sidebar: Just like Cursor, you get a sidebar (:AvanteToggle) for long-form chatting.

Inline Edits: You can select a block of code and press a key (usually <leader>aa) to ask the AI to refactor it. It shows a side-by-side diff inside Neovim so you can y (accept) or n (reject) the changes—exactly like Cursor's Cmd+K.

Codebase Context (@ Mentions): You can type @codebase in the chat to let the AI scan your project using RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation), or @file to pull in specific buffers.

Multi-file Editing: In "Agentic" mode, the AI can actually plan a change and apply it across multiple files in your project.

2. Why it beats the Web Subscription for you
Since you're using a Gemini API Key (which has a massive free tier for Gemini 3 Flash/Lite), you get a "Web-like" experience with these perks:

No Copy-Pasting: You aren't bouncing between Chrome and Neovim. You ask, and the code appears in your buffer.

Vim Keybindings: You use your existing motions to navigate the chat, search through history, and jump between the diffs.

Privacy/Control: Unlike the web interface, you can tell Avante exactly which files it’s allowed to see.

3. The "Gotchas" (Avante vs. Cursor)
While Avante is amazing, it's worth being realistic about two things:

Tab Autocomplete: Cursor has a custom "Copilot++" model for predicting your next few lines of code. Avante can do auto-suggestions, but it's not quite as "telepathic" as Cursor's native implementation.

Configuration: Cursor is "batteries included." Avante is a Neovim plugin—you'll need to install make, cargo (for the sidebar build), and a few dependencies like dressing.nvim or nui.nvim.

How to set it up (The "No-Bill" Config)
If you use lazy.nvim, add this to your plugins. This uses the Gemini Flash model which, as of 2026, has a free tier so generous it's basically impossible to hit as a single developer.

Lua
{
  "yetone/avante.nvim",
  event = "VeryLazy",
  build = "make", -- Important: builds the sidebar UI
  opts = {
    provider = "gemini",
    gemini = {
      model = "gemini-3-flash", -- The "current" high-speed model
      max_tokens = 8192,
    },
    -- This mimics Cursor's sidebar behavior
    mappings = {
      ask = "<leader>aa",
      edit = "<leader>ae",
      refresh = "<leader>ar",
    },
  },
}
The Verdict: If you want the power of the web-tier Gemini 3 but want to use your Neovim navigation to drive the car, Avante is the gold standard. It turns Neovim into a pro-grade AI IDE.

